The paper deals with polynomial identity testing, which is a fundamental problem in computational complexity theory and falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The use of read-once algebraic branching programs (RO-ABPs) and formulas suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of data structures (cs.DS). The algorithmic techniques used in the paper involve algebraic manipulations and analysis of polynomials, which are common in the sub-category of symbolic computation (cs.SC). The paper also involves the study of computational models and their expressive power, which is relevant to the sub-category of logic in computer science (cs.LO). Finally, the paper may be relevant to the sub-category of computational geometry (cs.CG) due to the use of algebraic geometry techniques in the analysis of RO-ABPs.
